data.content:
This is the **C# 14 Span overload resolution** breaking change. Here's what's happening:

**The problem:** In C# 14, `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. The `MemoryExtensions` method is not representable in expression trees, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

**The fix:** Force the call to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Before (breaks in .NET 10)
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.Contains(num);

// After (works)
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);
// or
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
// or call the static method explicitly:
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three options ensure the compiler picks the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which expression trees can represent.
